      "message": "\u003e On second thought, this doesn\u0027t compile.  But in chromium:\n\u003e \n\u003e ** Presubmit Warnings **\n\u003e Banned functions were used.\n\u003e     third_party/crashpad/crashpad/util/ios/exception_processor.mm:282:\n\u003e       New code should not use NULL. Use nullptr instead.\n\nI count 4 files that use NULL in all of Crashpad (excluding third_party), and the other three are all Windows code. We should fix those too.\n\nLemme guess, this doesn’t compile because nullptr isn’t compatible with function pointer types?\n\nNULL is just a macro that expands to 0 (or, really, for a 64-bit architecture, 0l), so that’s exactly equivalent to the existing working code, but Chromium’s presubmit won’t have any reason to hate it.\n\nC++ really seems to want you to use a literal 0 here, although I admit that it makes it look like you’re a n00b. To retain the nullptr, a bit_cast would work in reinterpret_cast’s place.",
